  "text": "In the log-lin plot shown in Figure 3 , whose slope shows the time departure of the aforementioned net-capture transients from pure exponential decays (straight lines in this plot), the \"set of slopes\" (instantaneous lifetimes) for (3) solved for an SBB ≈ 1.2 eV is wider than those shown in Figure 2 of [CITATION_1] . This has been sketched in Figure 3 to illustrate why surface-related transients in GaN devices such as HFETs have to be fitted by stretched exponentials [CITATION_2] . This would be a typical signature of these planar traps, where charge neutrality must be maintained for their DL during the transient and the capture barrier is modulated by trapped electrons as the surface ( ) increases with . This leads to transients that recall the left side of the bathtub curve widely used in reliability engineering (see Figures 8 and 9 of [CITATION_3] for example) when they are viewed with linear axis.",
